 In 1967, humans had not yet landed on the moon, and the computers at that time still seemed to fill the entire room like this. 

00:01:17.700 --> 00:01:21.290
 But at that time, wherever we flew, we were as fast as now, even faster than now. 

00:01:21.290 --> 00:01:26.690
 Why hasn't the flight speed increased in the past 50 years, but has become slower? 

00:01:26.690 --> 00:01:33.510
 First look at three commonly used aircraft engines: turboprop engines (turboprop engines), turbofan engines (turbofan engines) and turbojet engines (turbojet engines). 

00:01:33.510 --> 00:01:37.070
 Each engine has a most economical flight speed range 

00:01:37.070 --> 00:01:41.630
 You can see this turboprop on most aircraft with propellers 

00:01:41.630 --> 00:01:45.400
 For this kind of engine, almost all the thrust comes from the propeller 

00:01:45.400 --> 00:01:50.030
 Although the turbine used to drive the propeller can suck in and accelerate part of the air flow, 

00:01:50.030 --> 00:01:55.200
 But the air flow rate from the engine is not very fast, so the engine exhaust can only contribute less than 10% of the thrust 

00:01:56.200 --> 00:02:00.920
 As far as turboprop engines are concerned, because of their low purchase and operating costs, many short-distance regional commuter aircraft 

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:03.340
 All use turboprops as power 

00:02:03.340 --> 00:02:05.770
 Of course, no aircraft using this engine can fly very fast. 

00:02:05.770 --> 00:02:12.260
 The most economical speed of turboprop engines is between 325 miles per hour and 375 miles per hour. 

00:02:12.260 --> 00:02:15.600
 If you need to fly faster, it is best to use a turbofan engine 

00:02:15.600 --> 00:02:18.819
 Now you can see turbofan engines everywhere 

00:02:18.819 --> 00:02:22.200
 Most commercial aircraft are powered by turbofan engines. 

00:02:22.200 --> 00:02:26.290
 Turbo fan, as the name implies, air first needs to flow through a fan 

00:02:26.290 --> 00:02:28.040
 As you can see in front of the engine 

00:02:28.040 --> 00:02:32.480
 Then part of the air will flow into the internal combustion chamber 

00:02:32.480 --> 00:02:35.810
 Push the turbine to do work, used to drive the fan. A part of the air will pass through the periphery of the turbine. 

00:02:35.810 --> 00:02:40.550
 The part of the air passing from the periphery of the turbine actually passes through the outside duct. This part of the air is also accelerated 

00:02:40.550 --> 00:02:43.540
 And the main thrust of the turbofan engine is provided by the airflow ejected from the inner channel 

00:02:43.540 --> 00:02:48.920
 Most modern airplanes fly between 400-620 miles per hour, which is also the most economical speed of turbofan engines 

00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:56.709
 If you want to fly at supersonic speeds, which means that the speed exceeds 767 miles per hour, you need a turbojet engine (turbojet engine). 

00:02:56.709 --> 00:03:01.680
 Turbojet engines are very similar to turbofan engines. The difference is that all air flows through the turbine. 

00:03:01.680 --> 00:03:03.100
 No external culvert 

00:03:03.100 --> 00:03:08.620
 This allows the aircraft to reach very fast speeds, but at the cost of consuming a lot of fuel 

00:03:09.620 --> 00:03:14.500
 The turbojet engine's economic speed is between 1300-1400 miles per hour 

00:03:14.500 --> 00:03:19.180
 What really determines the efficiency of the aircraft engine is a value, called the "bypass ratio" 

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:24.220
 This is the ratio of the external culvert air flow and the engine core (internal tract) air flow 

00:03:24.220 --> 00:03:26.269
 This is the ratio of the external culvert air flow and the engine core (internal tract) air flow 

00:03:26.269 --> 00:03:31.569
 This is the case. In fact, driving a larger fan does not need to consume too much energy. 

00:03:31.569 --> 00:03:35.500
 But if you need more air to enter the engine, you need to increase the fuel supply 

00:03:35.500 --> 00:03:40.319
 In other words, under the same energy consumption, if more air can flow through the external culvert, you can get more thrust 

00:03:40.319 --> 00:03:46.680
 Therefore, this is like a law, that is, the greater the bypass ratio, the higher the engine efficiency 

00:03:47.700 --> 00:03:50.550
 Check out this GE GEnx engine 

00:03:50.550 --> 00:03:57.519
 This is a new ultra-high efficiency engine used on Boeing 787 Dreamliner and Boeing 747-8i Intercontinental airliner. 

00:03:57.519 --> 00:04:01.400
 You can see that the size of the fan is much larger than the turbine 

00:04:01.400 --> 00:04:07.280
 This is because this engine has a bypass ratio of 10:1. Means the air flow around the turbine (external duct) 

00:04:07.280 --> 00:04:09.020
 10 times the flow into the turbine 

00:04:09.020 --> 00:04:14.680
 In comparison, the efficiency of the older CFM56 engine produced by CFM International is lower 

00:04:14.680 --> 00:04:19.969
 You can see that the size of the fan is not so big compared to the turbine 

00:04:19.969 --> 00:04:24.430
 Because the bypass ratio of this engine is only 5.9:1, but it still belongs to the large bypass ratio 

00:04:24.430 --> 00:04:29.009
 If compared with Pratt &amp; Whitney's JT8D engine, the gap will be more obvious 

00:04:30.210 --> 00:04:36.330
 Because the bypass ratio of the JT8D engine is only 0.96:1, its efficiency is even lower 

