00:08:21.259 --> 00:08:27.159
 The consequence of this is that the flight speed is much lower than the speed of sound-767 miles per hour 

00:08:27.159 --> 00:08:30.439
 Why can't the plane fly close to the speed of sound? 

00:08:30.439 --> 00:08:34.500
 This chart shows the resistance of the aircraft at different speeds 

00:08:34.500 --> 00:08:39.409
 Between 0.8 and 1.2 Mach belongs to the "transonic" range (1 Mach is equivalent to 1 times the speed of sound) 

00:08:39.409 --> 00:08:44.930
 Within this range, the airflow around the aircraft is not completely subsonic or supersonic. 

00:08:44.930 --> 00:08:48.660
 Essentially, some airflows have exceeded the speed of sound, but there are still some airflows that have not reached the speed of sound 

00:08:48.660 --> 00:08:54.750
 So starting from Mach 0.8, part of the airflow has exceeded the speed of sound, which will increase the resistance sharply 

00:08:54.750 --> 00:08:59.441
 And reduce the aircraft's handling stability. So flying at speeds close to the speed of sound is very dangerous 

00:08:59.441 --> 00:09:03.129
 You need to fly far above the speed of sound or far below the speed of sound to be safe 

00:09:03.129 --> 00:09:06.940
 When the plane is flying at transonic speed, you can see this phenomenon 

00:09:06.940 --> 00:09:10.980
 Look at these stripes especially like scratches on the camera lens. Although this is hard to see. 

00:09:10.980 --> 00:09:14.459
 These stripes are actually miniature supersonic shock waves 

00:09:14.459 --> 00:09:20.020
 Because of the considerable resistance to air flow, when flying at a speed of 0.8 to 1.2 Mach 

00:09:20.020 --> 00:09:26.870
 It actually consumes more fuel than flying above Mach 1.2. This is why we have the number 613.8 mph 

00:09:26.870 --> 00:09:32.560
 This number is almost the speed limit of a modern subsonic jet 

